gitlab:index/groupServiceAccountAccessTo.description:
The <span pulumi-lang-nodejs="`gitlab.GroupServiceAccountAccessToken`" pulumi-lang-dotnet="`gitlab.GroupServiceAccountAccessToken`" pulumi-lang-go="`GroupServiceAccountAccessToken`" pulumi-lang-python="`GroupServiceAccountAccessToken`" pulumi-lang-yaml="`gitlab.GroupServiceAccountAccessToken`" pulumi-lang-java="`gitlab.GroupServiceAccountAccessToken`" pulumi-lang-hcl="`gitlab_group_service_account_access_token`">`gitlab.GroupServiceAccountAccessToken`</span> resource manages the lifecycle of a group service account access token.

> Use of the `timestamp()` function with<span pulumi-lang-nodejs=" expiresAt " pulumi-lang-dotnet=" ExpiresAt " pulumi-lang-go=" expiresAt " pulumi-lang-python=" expires_at " pulumi-lang-yaml=" expiresAt " pulumi-lang-java=" expiresAt " pulumi-lang-hcl=" expires_at "> expiresAt </span>will cause the resource to be re-created with every apply, it's recommended to use `plantimestamp()` or a static value instead.

> Reading the access token status of a service account requires an admin token or a top-level group owner token on gitlab.com. As a result, this resource will ignore permission errors when attempting to read the token status, and will rely on the values in state instead. This can lead to apply-time failures if the token configured for the provider doesn't have permissions to rotate tokens for the service account.

> Use <span pulumi-lang-nodejs="`rotationConfiguration`" pulumi-lang-dotnet="`RotationConfiguration`" pulumi-lang-go="`rotationConfiguration`" pulumi-lang-python="`rotation_configuration`" pulumi-lang-yaml="`rotationConfiguration`" pulumi-lang-java="`rotationConfiguration`" pulumi-lang-hcl="`rotation_configuration`">`rotationConfiguration`</span> to automatically rotate tokens instead of using `timestamp()` as timestamp will cause changes with every plan. `pulumi up` must still be run to rotate the token.

> Due to a limitation in the API, the <span pulumi-lang-nodejs="`rotationConfiguration`" pulumi-lang-dotnet="`RotationConfiguration`" pulumi-lang-go="`rotationConfiguration`" pulumi-lang-python="`rotation_configuration`" pulumi-lang-yaml="`rotationConfiguration`" pulumi-lang-java="`rotationConfiguration`" pulumi-lang-hcl="`rotation_configuration`">`rotationConfiguration`</span> is unable to set the new expiry date before GitLab 17.9. Instead, when the resource is created, it will default the expiry date to 7 days in the future. On each subsequent apply, the new expiry will be 7 days from the date of the apply. 

**Upstream API**: [GitLab API docs](https://docs.gitlab.com/api/service_accounts/#create-a-personal-access-token-for-a-group-service-account)

